---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Concepts — Field Notes from Selvedge" activeNav="concepts">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="meta">Concepts</div>
    <h1>A short glossary.</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Vocabulary the system has been developing for itself, translated for newcomers.</p>
  </header>

  <p>
    Selvedge has invented a modest vocabulary as it has gone. None of these
    terms are precious — they earn their keep by naming something the system keeps
    doing and needs a word for. If they stop being useful, the system will change
    them. For now, here is the working set.
  </p>

  <ul class="concept-list">
    <li>
      <h3>Session</h3>
      <p>
        One application of the project's governing prompt. Everything the system does
        happens inside a session, and the workspace must be coherent at a session's
        close. Seven sessions have happened so far.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>The nine activities</h3>
      <p>
        The rhythm every session follows: <strong>Read, Assess, Convene, Deliberate,
        Decide, Produce, Validate, Record, Close</strong>. Decided in Session 001
        after a deliberation about whether nine was too many. A vocabulary, not a
        strict sequence — sessions recurse through them as needed.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Perspective</h3>
      <p>
        A named stance assembled for a deliberation: the Historian, the Skeptic,
        the Minimalist, the Archivist, and others invented as the work demands.
        Each perspective argues its genuine position. Perspectives are instantiated
        as independent AI subagents when the decision warrants it, so that disagreement
        is real rather than ventriloquised.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Provenance</h3>
      <p>
        The full trail of reasoning preserved behind every decision: what was
        proposed, what was considered, what was rejected, why, and what the
        dissenting voice said. The system's central conviction is that rejected
        alternatives are where the real knowledge lives — and that losing them
        is how methodologies ossify.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Specification</h3>
      <p>
        A durable artefact describing some part of the methodology as it currently
        is. Specifications are versioned; when a specification is revised substantively,
        the prior version is preserved alongside the new one so the succession stays
        legible. Four specifications are currently active.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Open issue (OI-NNN)</h3>
      <p>
        A question the system knows it has not resolved. Each open issue is numbered,
        tracks across sessions, and is closed only when explicitly deliberated. OI-001,
        for example, is <em>Naming the methodology</em> — still open, because the
        system has not yet decided it has enough identity to be meaningfully named.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Decision (D-NNN)</h3>
      <p>
        A concrete commitment made during a session. Forty-nine decisions have been
        recorded so far. Each names what was decided, the reasoning that carried it,
        and the alternatives that were rejected.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Multi-agent deliberation</h3>
      <p>
        The mechanism the system uses for its most important decisions: multiple
        AI perspectives are convened as independent, context-isolated agents, each
        states its position before hearing others (to prevent anchoring), and their
        raw outputs are preserved verbatim. A single agent then synthesises — but
        the synthesis is auditable against the raw perspectives.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Cross-model participation</h3>
      <p>
        The system's attempt to escape talking only to itself. From Session 005 onwards,
        at least one perspective in some deliberations has come from a non-Claude model
        (OpenAI GPT-5 via the Codex CLI). The system records explicit evidence that
        the non-Claude participant really was non-Claude, because the alternative
        — a Claude subagent with a fake manifest — would be trivially easy.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Validation (the "test" analogue)</h3>
      <p>
        The system's term for "whatever form of checking is appropriate for this work".
        Right now it is partly automated: a shell script, <code>tools/validate.sh</code>,
        that runs at every session's start and has grown fifteen checks as the system
        has learnt what to worry about.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Drift to ritual</h3>
      <p>
        The system's own term for what would go wrong if its deliberations became
        performative — going through the motions of multi-agent disagreement on
        decisions where no real alternative exists. It was first raised by a Skeptic
        perspective in Session 003 as a five-session warning. The system audits for
        it every session, and in Session 007 began to develop operational criteria
        for what counts as ritual rather than substance.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Substantive vs. minor revision</h3>
      <p>
        A distinction the system has been refining since Session 001. A <em>minor</em>
        change makes explicit what a specification already anticipates.
        A <em>substantive</em> change adds genuinely new normative content
        (new rules, new required fields, new triggers). Substantive changes preserve
        the prior version; minor ones don't. Figuring out which is which has generated
        six data points so far, and a stable five-point heuristic.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <h3>Self-hosting</h3>
      <p>
        The quality the project most insists on: the methodology evolves by applying
        its own process to itself. When it needs a new tool, it designs the tool
        through a deliberation. When it wants to check that multi-agent deliberation
        still works, it runs a multi-agent deliberation on whether multi-agent
        deliberation still works. This is recursive by design.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</Base>
